where are some ironic statements that mr bennet makes in jane austen's pride and prejudice how are they justified and how are they irresponsible an unhappy alternative is before you elizabeth from this day you must be a stranger to one of your parents your mother will never see you again if you do not marry mr collins and i will never see you again if you do '' chapter xx of volume i elizabeth has just been asked for marriage by mr collins and her mother insists on her accepting the offer but she is not willing to marry collins him being a very silly man and she not being in love with him mr bennet is asked by mrs bennet to use his authority and oblige her to marry him mr bennet realizing elizabeth's feelings and knowing that collins is such a ridiculous character he ridicules his wife's unreasonable obsession of having her girls married to anyone who is wealthy enough mr bennet has common sense on his side while mrs bennet is just nonsensical the novel is full of such ironic remarks if i find some more i'll let you know Pride and Prejudice (BBC) Jane Austen Sense and Sensibility EastEnders Upstairs, Downstairs Friends Bride and Prejudice Sharon Tate Pride and Prejudice (2005 film) Polygamy Jane Eyre Novel Charmed Charles, Prince of Wales Alfred Hitchcock Jean Grey Little Britain Maison Ikkoku Phoebe Halliwell Mary Wollstonecraft Lou Gehrig Fathers' rights movement in the UK Beavis and Butt-head One Tree Hill (TV series) Days of our Lives Mary Jane Watson Fanny Burney Ranma __ characters Married... with Children Pitcairn sexual assault trial of 2004 Knots Landing Marilyn Monroe Maureen O'Sullivan Recurring South Park characters Random Harvest Bertrand Russell Jam (TV series) Prince Edmund (Blackadder) Charles Peace Another World (TV series) Hard Times Guiding Light Roman Catholic Church Brigadoon The Catcher in the Rye Episodes of Lost (Season 1) Yoko Ono L. S. Lowry Richard Boyle, 1st Earl of Cork Mansfield Park Neighbours Charles Dickens Joan Collins Dynasty (TV s